========,1,preface.
In mathematics, the arithmetic–geometric mean (AGM) of two positive real numbers and is defined as follows:
First, compute the arithmetic and geometric means of and , calling them and respectively (the latter is the principal square root of the product ):
Then, use iteration, with taking the place of and taking the place of .
In this way, two sequences and are defined:
These two sequences converge to the same number, which is the arithmetic–geometric mean of and ; it is denoted by , or sometimes by .
This can be used for algorithmic purposes as in the AGM method, which makes it possible to construct fast algorithms for calculating exponential and trigonometric functions, as well as some mathematical constants, in particular, to quickly compute ***formula***.
